  "prompt": "What is the concept behind 28 days in mobile packs in India?",
  "response": "In India, the concept of \"28 days\" in mobile packs refers to the standard validity period for prepaid mobile recharge plans. Traditionally, most mobile operators offer prepaid plans with a 28-day validity period, which is equivalent to roughly one month. This means:\n\n1. When a customer recharges their mobile number with a specific plan, the benefits (such as data, calls, and SMS) are valid for 28 days from the date of recharge.\n\n2. After 28 days, if the customer doesn't recharge again, the remaining benefits expire, and the number may become inactive.\n\n3. This 28-day cycle is different from a traditional calendar month and is designed to provide flexibility to users in terms of recharge timing.\n\nThe 28-day concept has been a common practice among telecom operators in India like Jio, Airtel, and Vodafone Idea. However, with increasing competition, some operators now offer plans with different validity periods to attract customers.\n\nThis system allows telecom companies to standardize their pricing and service offerings while providing customers with a predictable recharge cycle.",
